comments.body:
To test this, I used the following stack:

{
  "Parameters" : {
    "ImageId" : {
      "Type" : "String",
    },
  },
  "Resources" : {
    "Resource1" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Instance",
      "Properties" : {
        "ImageId" : {"Ref":"ImageId"}
      }
    },
    "Resource2" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Instance"
      "Properties" : {
        "ImageId" : {"Ref":"ImageId"}
      }
    },
    "Resource3" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Instance"
      "Properties" : {
        "ImageId" : {"Ref":"ImageId"}
      },
      "DependsOn" : "Resource1"
    },
    "Resource4" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Instance",
      "Properties" : {
        "ImageId" : {"Ref":"ImageId"}
      },
      "DependsOn" : "Resource2"
    },
    "Resource5" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Instance",
      "Properties" : {
        "ImageId" : {"Ref":"ImageId"}
      },
      "DependsOn" : "Resource3"
    }
  }
}

Run with the options -pImageId=<an imageId> -d and -t 1 to set the timeout for 1 minute.  What should happen is that all resources in euca-describe-resources should be either non-existant, in CREATE_FAILED or CREATE_COMPLETE when the stack fails.  It is possible for the stack to complete successfully, it depends on timing, but the work that was done put any resources that were in CREATE_IN_PROGRESS when the stack failed to CREATE_FAILED and also added stack events.
